<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus</i> <i>jeffreyi</i> and/or <i>Pinus</i> <i>ponderosa</i> is dominant to co-dominant with <i>Juniperus</i> <i>occidentalis</i>. Various shrub species such as <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>ledifolius</i> and <i>Purshia</i> <i>tridentata</i> characterize the understory. Associated herbs include <i>Carex</i> <i>rossii</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i> and <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 50 m; canopy is open to continuous. Shrub layer is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse to intermittent, or grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Pinus washoensis</i> > 50% relative cover in tree canopy and present in regeneration layer (Smith 1994).</li>
		
		<li><i>Pinus ponderosa</i> and/or <i>Pinus jeffreyi</i> is >30% relative cover in the tree layer with <i>Juniperus occidentalis</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> All slopes and aspects, but steep slopes, ridgetops, or plateaus are most common. Soils are shallow, often gravelly or coarse textured. May occur on skeletal, infertile or excessively-drained sites such as pumice, cinder or lava fields, and scree slopes. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> as a FACU plant. </div>
</div>

        
