<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> is the most widely distributed pine species in North America, growing from British Columbia to central Mexico and from Nebraska to the Pacific Coast. This long-lived conifer attains at least 50 m in height and up to 600 years in age. Seed production varies geographically and temporally, with high seed production every 2-7 years. Plants are shade intolerant. Seedling establishment is erratic and linked to periods of adequate soil moisture, high seed crop, and the availability of light mineral soil. It is best on light soils where extensive root proliferation is possible. The presence of grasses and shrubs reduces seedling survival. The status of this widespread species varies among the many forest types in which it occurs (Barbour et al. 2007a, Griffin and Critchfield 1972, Habeck 1992d, Oliver and Ryker 1990).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus jeffreyi </i>is a conifer that attains a height of 60 m and an age of 500 years. Trees produce large seed crops every 2-8 years. Cones shed their seeds in the fall, which are dispersed by wind, and by birds and small mammals that cache the seeds. Seedling establishment is best on bare soil. Trees are shade intolerant and grow most rapidly in nearly full sunlight. The species has an extensive range and grows in many habitats in the state (Barbour et al. 2007a, Habeck 1992b, Jenkinson 1980). Individual <i>P. jeffreyi </i>trees are present in many alliances and commonly occurs with <i>P. ponderosa</i>. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance is characterized by <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> and/or <i>Pinus jeffreyi</i> with shrub-dominated understories. Other trees such as <i>Abies concolor, Juniperus occidentalis,</i>or <i>Pinus contorta</i> can be present to co-dominant, but <i>Calocedrus decurrens</i> is typically absent. Stands generally consist of widely-spaced and scattered trees over a shrubby understory with a sparse herbaceous layer. Shrubs can form an open to moderately dense layer and the shrub composition varies depending on climate, soil, and overall vegetation density (NatureServe 2019). In California, some commonly associated shrub species are <i>Amelanchier utahensis, Arctostaphylos nevadensis, A. patula, Artemisia tridentata</i> (including ssp. <i>vaseyana</i>), <i>Ceanothus prostratus, Cercocarpus ledifolous, Prunus virginiana, Purshia tridentata,</i> and <i>Symphoricarpos</i> spp. (VegCAMP 2020).<br/>
<br/>
In general, stands of <i>P. ponderosa</i> and/or <i>P. jeffreyi</i> occur at low and montane elevations throughout California (Barbour et al. 2007a). However, this particular alliance is primarily found in the foothills of the Modoc Plateau and eastern Cascades at the lower ecotone between shrublands and more mesic coniferous forests. This alliance typically occurs on warm, dry, exposed sites (NatureServe 2019). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
