<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Trees are moderately resistant to fire (Habeck 1992b, Jenkinson 1990). Response to fire varies according to fire intensity, age, and season. Mature trees usually withstand most fires, but smaller trees are more susceptible. In general, <i>Pinus jeffreyi</i> and <i>Pinus ponderosa</i> are adapted to withstand low-intensity surface fires in stands with well-spaced trees. If stands have high tree densities and high fuel loads, fires are more intense and tree mortality high. <i>P. jeffreyi</i> is an early- to mid-seral species on productive sites, eventually replaced by more tolerant tree species, such as <i>Abies concolor</i>, under long fire intervals (Habeck 1992b, Sugihara et al. 2006).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
